  "query": "What are the benefits of creating rock pools on intertidal artificial structures for overall species richness?",
  "relevant_summary": "Creating rock pools on intertidal artificial structures provides significant benefits for overall species richness. Multiple replicated, controlled studies from Australia, the UK, Spain, and Malaysia have consistently shown that created rock pools support higher combined macroalgae, invertebrate, and fish species diversity and richness compared to structure surfaces without pools (Action ID: 3476). Specifically, nine of twelve replicated studies found increased species richness and diversity in created pools, with three studies reporting similar richness to natural rock pools. The pools support macroalgae, mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate, and fish species that are absent from structure surfaces without pools. Additionally, hole habitats and pit habitats on intertidal artificial structures have also been shown to increase combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and diversity on structure surfaces (Action IDs: 3467, 3475). A before-and-after study in Australia specifically reported that creating pools, along with reducing the slope of a structure, increased the combined macroalgae, invertebrate, and fish species richness on the structure.",
